<h1 id="exchange-adjustment" sourcefile="articles/finance/localizations/rus-exchange-adjustment.md" sourcestartlinenumber="28">Exchange adjustment</h1>


<p sourcefile="articles/finance/localizations/rus-exchange-adjustment.md" sourcestartlinenumber="32">On the reporting date, the Central Bank of Russia's exchange rate must be used to revalue the cash balance on a foreign currency bank account so that it correctly represents the cash balance value in the accounting currency. The exchange rate difference from the revaluation of the currency bank account is the difference between the value, in the accounting currency, of cash in the bank account on the date of the payment (or on the reporting date of the previous reporting period) and the value, in the accounting currency, of the cash in the bank account on the reporting date.</p>
<h2 id="accounting-of-exchange-rate-differences" sourcefile="articles/finance/localizations/rus-exchange-adjustment.md" sourcestartlinenumber="34">Accounting of exchange rate differences</h2>
<p sourcefile="articles/finance/localizations/rus-exchange-adjustment.md" sourcestartlinenumber="35">For accounting purposes, exchange rate differences are typically recorded as other income and expenses in the ledger account, such as <strong sourcefile="articles/finance/localizations/rus-exchange-adjustment.md" sourcestartlinenumber="35">ledger account 91 - Other income and expenses</strong>. For the purpose of income tax accounting, exchange rate differences are considered non-operational income and expenses.
The exchange rate difference on the currency bank account can be either positive (when the currency exchange rate increases) or negative (when the currency exchange rate decreases). The following table shows examples of ledger transactions for positive and negative exchange rate differences.</p>
